T","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mainwaring","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mesnil-Varin in Saint-Paër (Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie). The placename means ‘domain of Warin’ (see   Waring  ). Compare   Manwaring   and   Mandry  .","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó Manaráin</b>, see   Mannering   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Manwaring","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mainwaring  ."]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Mainwaring was born in 1110, in Cheshire, England, his father, Roger de Mainwaring, was 41 and his mother, Ellen Wayborn, was 31. He married Ann Thomas in 1128, in Warmingham, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1195, in Over Peover, Cheshire, England, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1110–1195":"1110–1195","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1107–Male":"1107–Surnud","1100–1200":"1100–1200","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1070–1119":"1070–1119","1080–1159":"1080–1159","1080":"1080","about 1195":"umbes 1195","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","Aft 1119":"pärast 1119","1070":"1070","1107":"1107","1128":"1128","1105":"1105","1159":"1159","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","before 1095":"enne 1095","1119":"1119","Over Peover, Middlewich, Cheshire, England":"Over Peover, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leek, Staffordshire, England":"Leek, Staffordshire, England","Over Peover, Cheshire, England":"Over Peover, Cheshire, England","Warmingham, Cheshire, England":"Warmingham, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1110–1195":"1110–1195","1105–Male":"1105–Kuollut","1107–Male":"1107–Kuollut","1100–1200":"1100–1200","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1070–1119":"1070–1119","1080–1159":"1080–1159","1080":"1080","about 1195":"noin 1195","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","Aft 1119":"1119 jälkeen","1070":"1070","1107":"1107","1128":"1128","1105":"1105","1159":"1159","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","before 1095":"ennen vuotta 1095","1119":"1119","Over Peover, Middlewich, Cheshire, England":"Over Peover, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Leek, Staffordshire, Englan